metadata.reasoningText:
Key insight from line 976-977: the list view inserts DOM nodes using `insertBefore`, maintaining a specific order:
```javascript
if (item.row.domNode.parentElement !== this.rowsContainer || item.row.domNode.nextElementSibling !== referenceNode) {
    this.rowsContainer.insertBefore(item.row.domNode, referenceNode);
}
```

This means DOM elements are inserted in order. But importantly, line 420-421:
```javascript
this.rowsContainer.style.overflow = 'hidden';
this.rowsContainer.style.contain = 'strict';


```

The rows container clips its content with `overflow: hidden` and creates a containment context with `contain: strict`, so its size is independent of its children. The container's height gets set to match the total scroll height of all items, which recalculates when items change—so when going from 4 items to 3, the height shrinks to 156px. But there's something I'm missing about how this affects the rendering...

Looking at the CSS transforms on each row, they're positioned using translateX and translateY based on their index. Row 0 stays at the origin, Row 1 shifts right and up by 52px, and so on. The transforms are moving items around within the 156px container, but I need to trace through exactly which items end up visible in the 208px viewport.

